<DOC><DOCNO> AP890125-0224 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2108EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-25 0472</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0481</SECOND><HEAD>Rain, Snow, Sleet Falls From Louisiana West to Rockies</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Wet weather extended Wednesday from northern Louisiana to theRockies, while most of the Southeast enjoyed temperatures in the 70s.   Snow was expected through Wednesday night in the White Mountainsof eastern Arizona. Snowfall overnight Tuesday in Arizona included 7inches at Pinetop, 5 inches at McNary, and 2 inches at Show Low.   Blowing and drifting snow continued Wednesday across the upperYellowstone Valley of south-central Montana.   Snow, freezing rain and sleet fell in the western OklahomaPanhandle.   Snow showers extended from much of Minnesota across northernWisconsin into Upper Michigan, across eastern South Dakota,northeast through southwest Nebraska, western Kansas, Colorado, andnorthern New Mexico. Snow and freezing rain reached from northernIowa into southern Minnesota.   Rain showers drenched northern Texas, Oklahoma, northernLouisiana, Missouri, western Illinois and the remainder of Iowa.Thunderstorms were scattered among the rain showers from northeastMissouri to north-central Texas.   Rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST included 1} inchesat Tulsa, Okla., almost an inch at Joplin, Mo., and aboutthree-quarters of an inch at San Antonio. Snowfall during the samesix hours included 3 inches at Pueblo, Colo., and an inch atLincoln, Neb., and Omaha, Neb.   Temperatures remained warm over much of the Southeast. Noontimetemperatures were in the 70s from South Carolina across Florida,over much of the central Gulf of Mexico states, Louisiana and theeastern quarter of Texas.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5degrees below zero at Idaho Falls, Idaho, to 81 degrees at McAllen,Texas. The low temperature for the nation Wednesday morning was 48degrees below zero at Wilson, Wyo.   The forecast for Thursday was for snow in Upper Michigan and fromNew England across much of inland New York, mixed with freezing rainin northeast Pennsylvania and south-central New York. Rain waspredicted from southeast and western New York across the remainderof Pennsylvania, Virginia, the Ohio Valley, lower Michigan, theTennessee Valley, much of Illinois, the southeast two-thirds ofMissouri, Arkansas, northern through western Louisiana, easternOklahoma and the northeast third of Texas. Rain showers, and snow inhigher elevations, were expected in Arizona into southeastCalifornia.   High temperatures were forecast to be in the teens in northernMaine, 20s and 30s in New England, New York, the upper Great Lakesregion, Minnesota, northwest Missouri, northern and central Plains,much of Oklahoma, the Rockies, the upper Missouri Valley, thenorthern Plateau and the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah.Highs should be in the 60s and 70s from the Virginias across centralFlorida, from the Tennessee Valley across the central Gulf of Mexicostates, and over Louisiana. Temperatures may reach the low 80s insoutheast Texas and southern Florida.</TEXT></DOC>